weekly_admissions_spec <- weekly_admissions_spec %>% 
  mutate(year = as.integer(str_sub(week_ending,1,4))) %>% 
  mutate(month = as.integer(str_sub(week_ending,5,6))) %>% 
  mutate(day = as.integer(str_sub(week_ending,7,8))) %>% 
  mutate(wdate = ymd(week_ending)) %>% 
  # identify "All Scotland" data
  mutate(hb_name = ifelse(hb=="S92000003","All Scotland",hb_name)) %>% 
  mutate(hb_name = ifelse(is.na(hb_name),"NHS Region Unknown",hb_name)) %>% 
  mutate(iswinter = ifelse(month %in% c(4,5,6,7,8,9),FALSE,TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(above_thresh = ifelse(percent_variation>0,7,0))
monthly_admissions_spec <- weekly_admissions_spec

monthly_admissions_spec <- monthly_admissions_spec %>% 
  group_by(hb, admission_type, speciality, year, month) %>% 
  summarise(monthly_admissions = 4*mean(number_admissions, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(mdate = as.Date(make_datetime(year, month, 15))) %>% 
  ungroup()

data_rolling <- weekly_admissions_spec %>% 
  filter(wdate > as.Date("2020-05-01")) %>% 
  filter(speciality == "All") %>% 
  filter(admission_type == "All") %>% 
  filter(hb_name =="All Scotland") %>%  
  mutate(
    moving_avg = slide_dbl(
      .x = number_admissions, 
      .f = ~ mean(., na.rm = TRUE),
      .before = 12,
      .after = 12,
      .complete = FALSE
    )
  )

Hypothesis Test

Is summer is significantly different to winter?

The null hypothesis is that the average value for summer is the same or lower than the average value for winter.

H0 : mean winter - mean summer <= 0 HA : mean winter - mean summer >0

we are setting alpha for this test to be 0.05

alpha=0.05
data_rolling %>% 
  filter(iswinter) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = mvar) +
  geom_histogram(col = "white")

seasonal_avg <- data_rolling %>%
  group_by(iswinter) %>% 
  summarise(mean= mean(mvar, na.rm=TRUE))
seasonal_avg
null_distribution <- data_rolling %>%
  filter(iswinter) %>%  
  specify(response = mvar) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "point", mu = 6.04) %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat = "mean")
null_distribution %>%
  visualise(bins = 30) + 
shade_p_value(obs_stat = seasonal_avg$mean[seasonal_avg$iswinter]
            , direction = "less")

 
p_value <- null_distribution %>% 
get_p_value(obs_stat = seasonal_avg$mean[seasonal_avg$iswinter]
            , direction = "less")
pull()
Error in UseMethod("pull") : 
  no applicable method for 'pull' applied to an object of class "NULL"
p_value

If pvalue is less than alpha we can reject null hypothesis

if(p_value > alpha){
 print("We cannot reject the null hypothesis. The average winter values are the same as the average summer values")
}else{
    print("We can reject the null hypothesis in favour of the alternative hypothesis. The average winter values are significantly different to the average winter values")}
